Route 7, or AK-7 as the locals begrudgingly call it, is less a highway and more a collection of disconnected asphalt whispers across the [Alaska Panhandle](/Alaska_Panhandle). It’s maintained by the [Alaska DOT&PF](/DOT%26PF), which, let's be honest, probably has better things to do, like contemplating the existential dread of potholes. The total length is a rather ambitious 144.62 miles, though this figure is somewhat misleading, as it’s scattered across four distinct sections. Think of it as a road that’s been broken up and distributed like party favors.

The "highway" is comprised of several segments, each with its own peculiar charm: the [South Tongass Highway](/South_Tongass_Highway) and [North Tongass Highway](/North_Tongass_Highway) near [Ketchikan](/Ketchikan,_Alaska); the [Mitkof Highway](/Mitkof_Highway) and [Nordic Drive](/Nordic_Drive) serving [Petersburg](/Petersburg,_Alaska); the rather grandly named [Egan Drive](/Egan_Drive) and [Glacier Highway](/Glacier_Highway) around [Juneau](/Juneau,_Alaska); and finally, the [Haines Highway](/Haines_Highway), which valiantly attempts to connect [Haines](/Haines,_Alaska) to the civilized world, or at least the Canadian border. There's also mention of [Old Glacier Highway](/Old_Glacier_Highway), which is apparently “Out the road,” a phrase that conjures images of forgotten dreams and questionable survival skills.

The [Alaska Marine Highway](/Alaska_Marine_Highway) plays a crucial role here, acting as the glue that attempts to hold these fragmented pieces together. Ferries, those majestic, lumbering vessels, dock in the connected cities, offering a watery reprieve from the terrestrial disappointments. However, the ports aren’t always conveniently located at the end of each segment, leading to a delightful abundance of dead ends. It’s a system designed for efficiency, I suppose, if your definition of efficiency involves a lot of backtracking and existential contemplation at the edge of the world.

### Route description

This section, according to the Federal [Manual on Uniform Traffic Control Devices](/Manual_on_Uniform_Traffic_Control_Devices) supplement for Alaska, is a masterpiece of bureaucratic nomenclature. AK-7, from south to north, snakes through:

*   The [South Tongass Highway](/South_Tongass_Highway) and [North Tongass Highway](/North_Tongass_Highway) in [Ketchikan](/Ketchikan,_Alaska). This is the southernmost segment, a 37.1-mile stretch that begins at a dead end near Ketchikan and reaches its northern limit at another dead end in [Ward Cove](/Ward_Cove,_Alaska). Within Ketchikan itself, it morphs through various street names – Tongass Avenue, Water Street, Front Street, Mill Street, and Stedman Street – before reclaiming its highway moniker. The ferry, of course, stops in Ketchikan, because that's how you get to places that are otherwise inaccessible by road.

*   [Nordic Drive](/Nordic_Drive) and [Mitkof Highway](/Mitkof_Highway) around [Petersburg](/Petersburg,_Alaska). This section is 34.21 miles long, originating at a dead end on [Mitkof Island](/Mitkof_Island) and terminating at Sandy Beach Road in Petersburg. Petersburg, naturally, boasts its own ferry terminal, because why wouldn’t it?

*   [Glacier Highway](/Glacier_Highway) and [Egan Drive](/Egan_Drive) in [Juneau](/Juneau,_Alaska). This is the longest continuous piece, spanning 39.01 miles. It starts at Franklin Street in [downtown Juneau](/Juneau,_Alaska) and marches north, traversing the [Juneau-Douglas Bridge](/Juneau-Douglas_Bridge) and eventually reaching a dead end near [Berners Bay](/Berners_Bay). The [Juneau International Airport](/Juneau_International_Airport) is conveniently located along this route, and the ferry docks at Auke Bay. There were once grand plans to extend this north of Berners Bay, a phantom called the [Lynn Canal Highway](/Lynn_Canal_Highway), but the state’s budget woes, a tale as old as time, have put that on indefinite hold. It’s a shame, really. Imagine the possibilities.

*   The [Haines Highway](/Haines_Highway). This 39.7-mile segment begins on Front Street in [Haines](/Haines,_Alaska), another port of call for the [Alaska Marine Highway](/Alaska_Marine_Highway), and heads northwest. It’s the road that actually *goes* somewhere, culminating at the [Dalton Cache–Pleasant Camp Border Crossing](/Dalton_Cache%E2%80%93Pleasant_Camp_Border_Crossing) near [Mosquito Lake](/Mosquito_Lake,_Alaska). From there, it seamlessly transitions into [Hwy 3](/Yukon_Highway_3) in [British Columbia](/British_Columbia), eventually linking up with the [Alaska Highway](/Alaska_Highway) at [Haines Junction](/Haines_Junction,_Yukon) in the [Yukon Territory](/Yukon_Territory). It’s the closest AK-7 gets to feeling like a real highway.

